        "role": "assistant",
        "content": "Maester Tomas sat at his desk, surrounded by a growing fortress of open books and unfurled scrolls. His candle had burned down to a stub, and he'd lit another without conscious thought. The afternoon light had faded from the high windows, replaced by the deep blue of early evening.\n\nHe had filled three pages with notes, cross-references, and increasingly pointed observations. His latest entry read:\n\n*\"The Battle of Greymarch (869 AE) - described in contemporary sources as 'putting down Conclave insurgents.' If treaty ratified in 847, why insurgents 22 years later? Why not criminals? Traitors? Language suggests ongoing legitimacy of Conclave as opposing force.\"*\n\nHe tapped his quill against his teeth, leaving a small ink mark he didn't notice. A thought occurred to him, and he pulled down yet another volume\u2014*The Lineages and Honors of the Northern Houses*.\n\n\"If Aldric's son was leading troops...\" He flipped through pages rapidly, squinting at the small print. \"Prince Gareth. Commanded the Northern Army from 855 to 871. Sixteen years of command during what should have been peacetime.\" He made another note. \"Against whom? If the war ended in 847, why maintain a standing army under royal command for decades?\"\n\nA knock at the door interrupted him. He looked up, irritated, expecting another apprentice with some trivial question.\n\n\"What?\" he barked.\n\nA young clerk entered hesitantly, carrying a sealed letter. \"Master Tomas, this just arrived from the Royal Archives. They said it was urgent.\"\n\nTomas's irritation vanished. He snatched the letter, broke the seal, and read quickly. His expression shifted from curiosity to alarm to something approaching fury.\n\nThe letter was brief:\n\n*\"Maester Tomas - Your apprentice has requested access to declassified materials. Per royal decree, all documents from the Third Magical War period require supervisory review before removal. Your presence is required to authorize the request. - Chief Archivist Morwen\"*\n\n\"Supervisory review,\" Tomas read aloud, his voice dripping with disdain. \"They declassify the documents but still control who sees them. Typical.\"\n\nHe stood, gathering his notes into a leather satchel with jerky, angry movements. \"Of course they require my presence. Can't have apprentices asking uncomfortable questions without a keeper present.\"\n\nHe paused, then grabbed several of the books he'd been consulting, adding them to his bag. If he was going to the archives anyway, he might as well bring his evidence of the circular sourcing problem.\n\nThe clerk still hovered by the door. \"Will you be going tonight, Maester?\"\n\n\"Immediately,\" Tomas said, already moving toward the door. Then he stopped and turned back, a thought occurring to him. \"Tell me\u2014this decree about supervisory review. When was it issued?\"\n\nThe clerk blinked. \"I... I don't know, Maester.\"\n\n\"Find out,\" Tomas ordered. \"I want to know if it predates the declassification or was issued in response to it.\" His eyes narrowed. \"Someone doesn't want these documents examined too closely. I intend to discover why.\"\n\nHe swept out of the study, robes billowing behind him, leaving the clerk staring after him in confusion.\n\nAs he descended the tower stairs, Maester Tomas found himself moving faster than he had in years, driven by something he hadn't felt in decades\u2014the scent of a genuine historical mystery, and the suspicion that someone was trying to control the narrative.\n\n\"Thirty years,\" he muttered again, but this time there was steel in his voice rather than defeat. \"If I've been wrong for thirty years, I'll be the one to prove it. Not some royal decree. Not some carefully managed declassification.\"\n\nThe evening air was cool as he emerged into the courtyard, heading toward the Royal Archives with the determined stride of a man who had just rediscovered his purpose."
