        "content": "Maester Tomas arrived at the Royal Archives as the last light faded from the sky. The building loomed before him, all grey stone and narrow windows, more fortress than library. He'd been here countless times over the decades, but tonight it felt different\u2014less like a repository of knowledge and more like a vault of secrets someone had finally, reluctantly, cracked open.\n\nThe main entrance guard recognized him immediately and stepped aside without question. Tomas descended the familiar marble stairs, his footsteps echoing in the vaulted space, then turned down a corridor he'd walked a thousand times. But at the third door on the left\u2014a door he'd passed countless times without a second thought\u2014he stopped.\n\nIt stood open now, revealing a descending staircase he'd never noticed before. Or perhaps had noticed and dismissed as storage, or restricted royal materials, or any of the dozen other sections scholars learned not to question.\n\n\"How long has this been here?\" he muttered to himself, beginning his descent.\n\nThe stairs were older than the main archive, he noted\u2014rougher stone, worn smooth in the centers by centuries of feet. The air grew cooler and carried that particular smell of very old parchment, the kind that had been sealed away from light and air for generations.\n\nAt the bottom, he found himself in a vast underground chamber that made him stop and stare despite himself. Rows upon rows of shelves stretched into the dimness, lit by scattered oil lamps that created pools of golden light in an ocean of shadow.\n\nAnd there, near the center, illuminated by a lamp on a reading table, was his apprentice, surrounded by unrolled scrolls like a dragon hoarding gold.\n\n\"I specifically told you,\" Tomas called out, his voice carrying across the stone chamber, \"to take proper notes. Not to go rummaging through documents without supervision.\"\n\nHe strode forward, his irritation warring with curiosity about what the apprentice had found. As he drew closer, he could see the scrolls spread across the table\u2014official seals, faded ink, the unmistakable format of military correspondence.\n\n\"What have you touched?\" he demanded, setting his satchel down with a heavy thump. \"And please tell me you've been wearing gloves. Documents this old are fragile, and your sweaty apprentice hands will\u2014\"\n\nHe stopped mid-sentence, his eyes falling on the scroll nearest to him. Even from this angle, he could see the date: 878 AE. And the header: *\"Royal Decree Regarding Continued Hostilities with the Mage Conclave.\"*\n\nHis hand reached out involuntarily, then stopped. He pulled a pair of thin leather gloves from his robe pocket\u2014he always carried them\u2014and slipped them on before carefully rotating the scroll to read it properly.\n\n\"Continued hostilities,\" he read aloud, his voice barely above a whisper. \"In 878. Thirty-one years after the supposed treaty.\" He looked up at the apprentice, and his expression was complex\u2014anger at the apprentice's recklessness, but also something like vindication. \"What else have you found?\""
