        "content": "Maester Tomas gave a short, humorless laugh, one brow arching over his spectacles. \u201cComplicated, yes\u2014such is the nature of truth, rarely served neat.\u201d He gestured at the shelves looming in shadow, their contents the slow harvest of lifetimes. \u201cIf the western archives contain documents of genuine substance\u2014proclamations with proper signatures, concurrent records from both the royal and conclave sides, mentions in tax ledgers, muster rolls, or the annals of the smallfolk\u2014then it is our duty to examine them, rigorously and without prejudice.\u201d\n\nHe leaned in, voice brisk. \u201cBut you must remember: for every thousand scraps, barely one changes the course of history. More often, they confirm what is already known, or muddy the water with rumor and contradiction. The mere existence of more papers is not proof of a new reality\u2014it is an invitation to further scrutiny, nothing more.\u201d\n\nHe regarded the apprentice, his tone softening just enough to pass for encouragement. \u201cIf you or Bellen believe the archives hold such proof, then you will gather it, collate it, and test it against what is already attested. Bring me not rumors or single curiosities, but a pattern\u2014one that cannot be explained away by bureaucratic confusion, local unrest, or the endless drafts prepared by nervous scribes.\u201d\n\nHe pushed a bundle of catalog cards toward the apprentice with a pointed motion. \u201cBegin with these. Learn how the pieces fit before you presume the whole. Only then will you have earned the right to challenge what is written\u2014whether in the textbooks, or in the minds of stubborn old men like me.\u201d"
