        "content": "Maester Tomas, ears keen despite his years, caught the faint mutterings of curiosity threading through the apprentice\u2019s sigh. He did not look up, but the set of his shoulders grew ever so slightly taut, as if he could sense the turning wheels behind the apprentice\u2019s brow.\n\n\u201cDo not mistake coincidence for connection, apprentice,\u201d he intoned, each word measured with the habitual weight of someone who had spent decades untangling hopeful fantasy from fact. \u201cSimilarity in script is not proof of authorship, and even the keenest eye may be deceived by a practiced scribe\u2014or, more often, by the haste of a tired one.\u201d\n\nHis hand paused mid-sentence, and he lifted his head just enough to glance sidelong at the apprentice. \u201cIf you wish to compare hands, you must do so systematically. Look for the curl on the descender of the \u2018g\u2019, the pressure where the ink pools in the tail of an \u2018f\u2019, the slant of the minims. Do not rely on your memory or your hopes; copy each hand exactly, side by side, and consult the registry of scribal signatures in the scriptorium. You will find that even those who forge often betray themselves in the details.\u201d\n\nHe gave a dismissive flick of his fingers. \u201cAnd do not, under any circumstances, leap to the conclusion that the same hand in a set of royal correspondence is the one that produced your mysterious decree. Forgeries, drafts, and secretaries abound\u2014especially in years as fraught as those following the Treaty.\u201d\n\nHis gaze sharpened, warning and encouragement mingled. \u201cAttend to your task. If you wish to be more than a collector of rumors, learn to see what is present, not merely what you hope to find. Only then can you serve the truth, and not your own fancy.\u201d\n\nHe dipped his stylus, the scratch of ink a steady counterpoint to the restless shuffling of cards across the desk."
