        "content": "Noor found a working burner on the stove, lit it with a match from a box by the sink. The soup started to bubble almost immediately \u2014 thin, pale broth with anemic noodles floating like worms. They stirred it with a wooden spoon that had someone else's teeth marks on the handle.\n\nWhile it heated, Noor moved back to the laptop. Sat down. Pulled the encrypted drive closer and entered the password \u2014 a sixteen-character string they'd memorized, never written down. The drive opened.\n\nForty-three files. PDFs, spreadsheets, scanned documents. Noor had looked through maybe a dozen of them before coming up here. Now they opened the one labeled \"MERIDIAN_PAYMENTS_2019-2023.xlsx\" and started scrolling.\n\n\"Jesus,\" they muttered.\n\nThe payments were routed through shell companies in Delaware and the Caymans, but the pattern was clear once you knew what to look for. Municipal contracts awarded in March. Payments flowing out in April. The same five names on every approval board. And the amounts \u2014 Noor did quick mental math \u2014 the amounts added up to somewhere north of forty million dollars.\n\nTheir source had been one of those five names. Until six months ago, when they'd apparently grown a conscience.\n\nThe soup started to boil over. Noor lunged for the stove, turned it off, slopped some of the soup onto the counter in their haste. They swore under their breath, grabbed a dishrag that smelled like mildew, wiped it up.\n\nThey poured the soup into one of the three mugs \u2014 the one that said \"World's Best Grandpa\" \u2014 and carried it back to the table. Took a sip. It tasted like hot salt water and regret, but it was food.\n\n\"The last payment was eight weeks ago,\" Noor said aloud, even though they were mostly talking to themselves now. They pulled up another file \u2014 this one a scanned memo with a county seal at the top. \"Right before the infrastructure vote. Twenty-two million for road repairs that never happened.\"\n\nThey ate more soup, scrolling with their other hand.\n\nTheir phone sat face-up on the table, still showing no signal. Noor picked it up anyway, checked it. Put it down. Picked it up again thirty seconds later.\n\n\"They should have called before they left,\" Noor said, quieter now. \"That was the protocol. Call from a payphone, let it ring twice, hang up. Then drive. But there was no call, and now...\"\n\nThey trailed off, set the phone down harder than necessary.\n\nThe soup was half-gone. Noor's eyes felt grainy, like someone had poured sand under the lids. They blinked hard, refocused on the screen. Opened another file \u2014 a photograph this time. A parking lot, taken from a distance. Two men shaking hands next to a black SUV. Noor zoomed in on the license plate, then cross-referenced it against a database they definitely weren't supposed to have access to.\n\nThe plate came back registered to a holding company. The holding company's address was a PO box in Delaware. The registered agent was a law firm that Noor recognized from three other stories about three other bodies.\n\n\"Okay,\" they said softly. \"Okay, okay, okay.\"\n\nThey grabbed a legal pad from their bag, started making notes in shorthand. Names, dates, dollar amounts. Drew lines connecting them. Their handwriting got messier as they went faster, chasing the thread.\n\nThe mug of soup sat forgotten, getting cold again.\n\nOutside, something made a sound \u2014 maybe an animal, maybe a branch falling. Noor's head snapped up, their whole body going tense. They sat frozen, listening. Thirty seconds passed. A minute. Nothing else.\n\nNoor exhaled slowly and went back to the notes.\n\n\"If the source doesn't show,\" they said, \"I need to verify at least three of these payments independently. Bank records, meeting minutes, something that'll hold up.\" They were talking to themselves again, working through it. \"The county clerk's office opens at eight. I can submit a FOIA request, but that'll take weeks, and if someone's already...\"\n\nThey stopped. Rubbed their eyes with the heels of their hands.\n\nWhen they looked up again, their gaze landed on Driver. \"You should try to sleep,\" Noor said. \"One of us should. I'll wake you if anything happens.\"\n\nThey turned back to the laptop before waiting for an answer, already opening the next file."
