        "content": "Noor looked up from the laptop, and for the first time since they'd arrived at the cabin, something in their expression softened. Not relief, exactly \u2014 more like the small easing that came from not being alone with the fear anymore.\n\n\"Thank you,\" they said quietly. Then, more businesslike, because gratitude made them uncomfortable: \"Okay. Yeah. There's actually something.\"\n\nThey pulled the legal pad closer, flipped to a page covered in names and phone numbers. \"I have a list of county employees who would've had to sign off on these contracts. Most of them are probably clean \u2014 just doing their jobs, didn't know what they were approving. But someone had to know.\"\n\nNoor tapped one name, circled in red. \"Margaret Voss. She was the deputy director of public works until last year. Retired suddenly, moved to Arizona. The source mentioned her once \u2014 said she 'knew where the bodies were buried,' which at the time I thought was a figure of speech.\"\n\nThey pulled up a browser, navigated to a people-search site. \"I need to find a current phone number for her. The one I have just rings and rings \u2014 probably disconnected. Can you try the usual places? Facebook, LinkedIn, any of those neighborhood directory sites? Sometimes people list their new numbers without realizing it.\"\n\nNoor stood, stretched, their spine making a series of concerning pops. They moved to the window again \u2014 the third or fourth time in the last hour \u2014 and checked the road. Still empty.\n\n\"If we can get her on the phone, even just to confirm she remembers the source, that's something,\" Noor continued, moving back to the table. \"If she'll talk to me, that's everything. She's got thirty years in that department. She knows how the money moved.\"\n\nThey paused, looking at Driver properly. \"Your phone has signal up here, right? Mine's locked to a carrier that apparently doesn't believe in mountains.\"\n\nNoor pulled their own phone closer, checked it again even though they knew what it would say. Still nothing.\n\n\"And\u2014\" They hesitated, then reached into their jacket pocket and pulled out a small USB drive, different from the encrypted one. This one was bright blue, cheap-looking. \"If something happens. If someone does come up that road and we have to run. You take this.\"\n\nThey held it out. \"It's a copy. Not everything \u2014 I couldn't fit it all \u2014 but enough. The payment records, the key emails, photos of the source's documents. If I don't make it out, or if they get the laptop, you get this to my editor. Her name's Patricia Ruiz, she's at the Chronicle. Don't mail it, don't email it. Hand it to her directly.\"\n\nNoor's hand was steady as they held out the drive, but their voice was quieter. \"I'm not trying to be dramatic. I just need to know someone else has it. That it won't just... disappear with me.\"\n\nThey waited for Driver to take it, then moved back to the laptop. Pulled up another spreadsheet, this one tracking construction contracts by date and amount.\n\n\"Margaret Voss,\" they repeated, refocusing. \"Anything you can find. Phone number, address, email. Even a Facebook message would work at this point.\"\n\nTheir fingers moved across the keyboard, pulling up another file. The cabin was quiet except for the clicking of keys and the occasional creak of old wood settling. Outside, the wind picked up, rattling something against the side of the cabin.\n\nNoor's eyes flicked toward the sound, then back to the screen. They were running on fumes now \u2014 coffee and adrenaline and the stubborn refusal to stop moving because stopping meant thinking about what three hours late probably meant.\n\n\"I'll make fresh coffee,\" they said suddenly. \"The terrible coffee is better than no coffee at this point.\""
