        "role": "assistant",
        "content": "Noor moved to the coffee maker, dumped the cold sludge from earlier, and rinsed the pot in the sink. The water came out rust-colored for the first few seconds before running clear. They found the bag of pre-ground coffee in the cabinet \u2014 some generic brand that was probably older than it should be, but at this point, who was counting?\n\nWhile the coffee maker gurgled and hissed, Noor leaned against the counter and watched Driver scroll through their phone. It felt strange, having someone else working the problem with them. Most of the last six months had been solo work \u2014 following paper trails in dusty county offices, meeting sources in parking garages, sitting alone in their apartment at 3 AM connecting dots that nobody else wanted connected.\n\n\"Margaret had a daughter,\" Noor said suddenly, remembering. \"Emily, maybe? Or Emma. She posted about her retirement party on Facebook last year \u2014 I saw it when I was doing the initial research. Might be tagged in the daughter's photos if she's not active on her own account.\"\n\nThe coffee finished brewing. Noor poured two mugs \u2014 the \"World's Best Grandpa\" one they'd used for soup, hastily rinsed, and another that said \"I'd Rather Be Fishing.\" They brought both to the table, set one near Driver.\n\n\"Here.\" They took a sip from their own mug, winced. It was better than the cold stuff, but not by much. \"God, that's awful.\"\n\nNoor sat back down at the laptop, pulled up a new document, and started typing. Their fingers moved fast, muscle memory from years of turning scattered thoughts into coherent prose.\n\n*Margaret Voss served as deputy director of public works for Riverside County from 1992 to 2023. During her tenure, she oversaw the approval process for more than $200 million in municipal contracts. According to sources familiar with the matter, Voss raised concerns about irregularities in the bidding process for the 2019 infrastructure project, but those concerns were never formally documented.*\n\nThey paused, reread what they'd written, then kept going.\n\n*Voss retired abruptly in March 2023, three months after the final payment was processed for the Meridian contracts. Attempts to reach her for comment have been unsuccessful.*\n\n\"I'm writing it,\" Noor said aloud, not looking up from the screen. \"Even if I can't publish it yet, I'm writing it. Because if something happens to me, if the source doesn't show, at least there's a draft. Something that exists outside my head.\"\n\nThey took another sip of terrible coffee, then another. Their leg was bouncing under the table \u2014 a nervous tic they couldn't seem to stop.\n\n\"Find anything?\" they asked, glancing at Driver's phone."
