        "content": "Chief Hoang, who had just begun to reseal a coupling on the coolant loop, paused. Her hand, still holding the wrench, hovered in mid-air. She slowly straightened up, turning to face the junior officer once more. The sigh that escaped her this time was less weary, more... resigned.\n\nShe looked at the junior officer, then at the tablet still open in their hand, then back at the junior officer. Her expression was a complex mixture of disbelief and an almost clinical assessment of the question.\n\n\u201cSolid waste,\u201d Chief Hoang repeated, her voice flat, devoid of inflection. \u201cCompressed into pellets. Ejected really fast.\u201d She allowed a moment of silence to pass, the hum of the life support pumps filling the void.\n\n\u201cJunior Officer,\u201d she began, her tone measured, \u201clet us consider the physics of that. First, the mass. Even if we collected every gram of solid waste produced by the entire crew over a significant period, we are talking about a few kilograms per day, perhaps a hundred over a week. Compared to the hundreds of thousands of metric tons of this vessel, the total mass available for reaction mass is, again, negligible. The delta-v you would achieve from such a system would be, at best, fractions of a meter per second. You would expend more energy compressing and ejecting the pellets than you would gain in propulsion.\u201d\n\nShe then moved to the practicalities, her eyes narrowed slightly. \u201cSecond, the engineering. To \u2018compress into pellets and eject really fast\u2019 would require a dedicated propulsion system. A high-velocity mass driver, specifically designed to handle heterogeneous biological material. The energy requirements for such a system would be immense. The maintenance alone would be a nightmare. We would need to divert power from our primary systems, perhaps even our life support, to operate a waste ejector that provides almost zero propulsive benefit.\u201d\n\nChief Hoang walked over to a nearby workstation and tapped a few keys, bringing up a schematic of the vessel's waste management system. \u201cOur current solid waste system is designed for containment, breakdown, and eventual reclamation of useful elements, not propulsion. It\u2019s about hygiene and resource cycling. It ensures we don\u2019t become a biohazard, and that we recycle every drop of water and nutrient possible. Repurposing it for a thrust mechanism would compromise critical life support functions for an unquantifiably small return.\u201d\n\nShe turned back to the junior officer, her gaze unwavering. \u201cYou\u2019re thinking like a rocket scientist who has an infinite supply of fuel and no regard for the internal environment of their spacecraft. We are a closed ecosystem, Junior Officer. Every resource, every kilogram, every watt of power, is accounted for and has a critical purpose in keeping us alive. Diverting or incinerating our waste for propulsion is not only inefficient to the point of being useless, but it would also introduce significant health and resource management problems.\u201d\n\n\u201cNo,\u201d Chief Hoang concluded, her voice leaving no room for argument. \u201cWe do not use solid waste for thrust. The numbers simply do not work, and the engineering cost and biological risk are astronomically high for effectively zero benefit.\u201d"
