        "role": "assistant",
        "content": "Hoang stopped humming the moment the words left the junior officer's mouth. She didn't look up immediately. She finished the turn of the wrench on the manifold fitting, then set the tool down on the tarp with a deliberate clink. She wiped her hands on a rag, the grease dark against her skin, before lifting her gaze to meet the officer's eyes. There was no heat in her look, only the flat, assessing weight of someone who had calculated a thousand ways to die and decided against most of them.\n\n\"Venting the main atmosphere isn't a propulsion strategy. It's a hull breach with a timer,\" she said. Her voice remained level, carrying the resonance of the bay's vibration without rising above it. \"You want to know why that idea will get you killed before you reach the asteroid belt?\"\n\nShe gestured vaguely toward the ceiling, where the ventilation ducts hummed. \"The scrubbers aren't just filters. They rely on the specific density and pressure of the main loop to drive the chemical reaction that converts CO2 into solid carbonates. If you vent that, the scrubbers fail. The CO2 partial pressure spikes within twenty minutes. You don't suffocate from lack of oxygen; you suffocate from poisoning. And the heat exchange loops? They're open to the void now. You'll lose thermal regulation faster than the suits can compensate.\"\n\nHoang picked up the chalk, tapping the tip against the manifold housing. \"Even if you ignored the life support, the thrust vector would be uneven. You'd torque the ship. Mass ratio is the enemy here. Air is heavy and slow to exhaust compared to reaction fuel. You'd need to vent half the ship to get the acceleration you want. The structural integrity of the hull might not take the pressure differential without warping the welds.\"\n\nShe set the chalk down on the tarp, marking the end of the conversation. \"We have fuel for a reason. It's denser, safer, and it doesn't involve stripping the ship's skin. Do not speak of venting the atmosphere as a maneuver again. If you see a situation where that might be viable, assume you've misdiagnosed the problem. Return to your station.\"\n\nShe turned back to the coolant loop, signaling the interview was over, and went back to work."
