        "role": "assistant",
        "content": "Hoang watched the door hiss shut, the magnetic locks engaging with a heavy, final sound. The silence that followed was not empty; it was charged with the potential for failure. She did not move immediately. She let the moment settle, her eyes tracking the pressure gauge on the wall where the emergency reserve tanks were located.\n\nShe tapped her wrist comms, establishing the direct feed to the bridge. \"Bridge, this is Engineering,\" she said, her voice flat. \"Initiate remote override on the emergency reserve line. Confirming the safety kill-switch is active on the main console. I will be monitoring from the bridge in ten minutes. If I don't see the coupling stabilizing within that window, I am cutting power to the venting manifold regardless of the burn time. Do not argue with the telemetry.\"\n\nThe static crackled, followed by the acknowledgment. She disconnected the link and returned to her workstation. The risk was real. The atmosphere was heavy, dense, and lethal if mishandled. She picked up her wrench again, focusing on the bolt she had been tightening. It needed to be perfect. If the venting caused a resonance in the hull, a single loose bolt could cascade into a rupture.\n\nShe torqued the bolt to specification. The metal groaned, then held. She exhaled, the sound barely audible over the hum of the ship.\n\n\"Don't make me regret this,\" she murmured to the empty bay.\n\nShe moved to the control panel, pulling up the diagnostic screens for the life support system. She needed to ensure the scrubbers could handle the pressure drop from the reserve tanks. If the scrubbers failed during the burn, the crew would be fine for a while, but the air would become toxic. It was a chain reaction she couldn't afford.\n\nShe opened her toolkit, checking her calipers and pressure gauges. She would move to the bridge for the burn, but for now, she needed to be where the pipes were, in case the bridge couldn't see the physical failure. She adjusted her position, moving to a vantage point where she could see the venting manifold's rigging while the officer worked. She would be close enough to cut the line with her own hands if the telemetry lied.\n\nShe pulled up the schematics again, reviewing the isolation protocols she had authorized. Her eyes scanned the red lines of the emergency reserve. She had approved the burn, but the responsibility for the outcome was now on her hands. She would not let the math fail her.\n\n\"Get it done right,\" she said, her voice finding the quiet authority that usually preceded a crisis. She turned her attention back to the pump coupling, her mind already calculating the stress points of the maneuver. The clock was ticking."
