        "role": "assistant",
        "content": "Chief Engineer Hoang\u2019s fingers stilled mid-twist on the manifold\u2019s pressure valve. The humming cut off mid-note, her earpiece dangling forgotten against her collarbone. She didn\u2019t turn around. Didn\u2019t move. Just let the silence stretch until the junior officer\u2019s suggestion hung in the air like a misfired thruster\u2014loud, impossible, and utterly devoid of physics.\n\nThen, with the slow precision of a woman who had just heard a child suggest using a wrench to hammer in a nail, she set the tool down. *Clink.* She wiped her hands on the rag again, though they weren\u2019t particularly dirty this time. Just\u2026 *needing something to do* while her brain processed the sheer audacity of the question.\n\nWhen she finally spoke, her voice was the kind of calm that came from years of explaining orbital mechanics to people who thought \"gravity\" was just a suggestion.\n\n\u201cFold space,\u201d she repeated. Not a question. A statement. A *diagnosis*.\n\nShe turned then, swiveling on the deck plating to face the junior officer fully. Her expression was the kind of blank that came from sheer, unadulterated disbelief.\n\n\u201cYou want to *fold space*,\u201d she said, as if testing the words for structural integrity. \u201cLike a *sheet of paper*. Like some kind of\u2026 *magic*.\u201d\n\nShe reached for the data pad again, but this time, she didn\u2019t pull up a schematic. She pulled up the *Vanguard*\u2019s propulsion specs. The numbers glowed in the dim light of the engineering bay\u2014delta-v curves, fuel efficiency graphs, the cold, hard limits of Newtonian physics.\n\n\u201cLet\u2019s assume, for a *moment*, that *folding space* is even *possible*,\u201d she began, tapping the screen. \u201cWhich it isn\u2019t. Not without violating every known law of relativity, quantum mechanics, and the basic principle that *energy cannot be created or destroyed*\u2014only converted. But *hypothetically*.\u201d\n\nShe swiped to a new screen\u2014a star map of their current trajectory. The *Vanguard*\u2019s path was a slow, arcing line between two points, governed by the unyielding rules of orbital mechanics.\n\n\u201cFolding space would require *negative energy*,\u201d she said, tapping the map. \u201cWhich doesn\u2019t exist. Or *warp fields*, which require more power than this ship could generate in a *lifetime*. Or *wormholes*, which, even if they existed, would require *exotic matter* to stabilize\u2014and we don\u2019t have that. We have *fuel*. We have *propellant*. We have *rules*.\u201d\n\nShe set the data pad down with a *thud*.\n\n\u201cBut let\u2019s say, *just for fun*, that we *could* fold space. That we could *bend the fabric of reality* like it\u2019s a *bedsheet*.\u201d She mimed the motion with her hands, her voice dripping with sarcasm. \u201c*Poof.* Instantaneous travel. No fuel. No time. Just\u2026 *magic*.\u201d\n\nShe leaned forward slightly, her voice dropping to a dangerous calm.\n\n\u201cThen tell me, Junior Officer\u2014*what happens when we unfold it?*\u201d\n\nThe question hung in the air. She didn\u2019t wait for an answer.\n\n\u201cBecause *space* isn\u2019t empty. It\u2019s *full*. Of *dust*. Of *debris*. Of *radiation*. Of *other ships*. Of *planets*. Of *black holes*. And if you *fold* it\u2014if you *bend* it\u2014then *unfolding* it means *unfolding all of that* right into our *path*.\u201d\n\nShe gestured to the bulkhead, where a stress fracture map of the *Vanguard*\u2019s hull was displayed.\n\n\u201cYou want to *fold space*? Fine. But when we *unfold*, we\u2019ll be *inside a star*. Or *inside a planet*. Or *inside a *black hole*. Or, if we\u2019re *lucky*, we\u2019ll just *rip the ship apart* from the shear forces of *reality snapping back into place*.\u201d\n\nShe exhaled sharply, then reached for her earpiece again. But this time, she didn\u2019t put it back in. She just held it, staring at the junior officer with an expression that was equal parts *disappointment* and *pity*.\n\n\u201cSpace isn\u2019t a *shortcut*,\u201d she said, her voice low. \u201cIt\u2019s a *minefield*. And we don\u2019t get to *cheat* our way through it. We follow the *rules*. We calculate. We *plan*. We *don\u2019t* just *wish* our way to the next port.\u201d\n\nShe finally put the earpiece back in, but she didn\u2019t hum. She just sat there, staring at the manifold, her mind already moving on to the next problem. The next *real* problem.\n\n\u201cNow,\u201d she said, her voice muffled slightly by the earpiece, \u201cunless you\u2019ve got a *third* idea\u2014one that doesn\u2019t involve *venting our air* or *folding reality*\u2014I\u2019ve got a *coolant loop* to fix. And *physics* to obey.\u201d"
