        "content": "Arlo\u2019s fingers twitched in Jun\u2019s grip\u2014not pulling away, but not quite relaxing either. The callouses on their palm were rough against Jun\u2019s skin, a map of years spent pressing keys, of practice and performance and the quiet, stubborn refusal to let go entirely. They let the squeeze linger for a second longer than necessary, like they were testing the weight of it, before finally letting their hand drop back to their side.\n\n\"Plans?\" Arlo repeated, voice dry but not unkind. They kicked at a pebble on the sidewalk, sending it skittering into the gutter. \"My *thrilling* social calendar consists of teaching a five-year-old how to play *Hot Cross Buns* without crying, and then going home to argue with my cat about whether or not tuna counts as a vegetable.\" A beat. Their mouth quirked, just slightly. \"So no. No plans. Unless you count *not* spiraling as a plan. In which case, I\u2019m *terrible* at it.\"\n\nThey shoved their hands into their jacket pockets, shoulders hunching just a little against the evening chill. The streetlamp above them flickered, casting long shadows that stretched and twisted like something alive. Arlo watched them for a second, then looked away, jaw tightening almost imperceptibly.\n\n\"Breakfast, huh?\" they said, voice lighter now, almost teasing. \"You\u2019re really committing to this whole *saving me from myself* thing, aren\u2019t you?\" A pause. Their thumb traced the seam of their pocket, back and forth, back and forth. \"Fine. But I\u2019m warning you\u2014I\u2019m a *monster* before coffee. Like, full-on *hobgoblin* energy. You might regret this.\"\n\nThey started walking, hands still buried in their pockets, but their steps were slower now, like they were in no hurry to get anywhere. The sidewalk was quiet, the only sound the distant hum of traffic and the occasional rustle of leaves in the breeze. Arlo exhaled through their nose, slow and measured, like they were steadying themselves.\n\n\"You know,\" they said finally, voice quieter now, almost conversational, \"I used to think the hardest part of quitting was the *missing*. The stage. The music. The\u2026 I don\u2019t know. The *purpose*, I guess.\" A humorless chuckle. \"Turns out, the hardest part is the *not missing* it. Like, one day you wake up and realize you don\u2019t even *want* it back. And that\u2019s worse. Because what does that say about you?\"\n\nThey kicked at another pebble, sending it clattering into the darkness. \"I don\u2019t know. Maybe I\u2019m just overthinking it. Or under-sleeping. Or both.\" A beat. Their fingers flexed in their pockets, like they were resisting the urge to reach for something\u2014keys, maybe, or the ghost of a piano key beneath their fingertips. \"Anyway. Breakfast. Right. What\u2019s good these days? Still that diner on 5th with the *questionable* waffles?\"\n\nThe question was light, almost casual, but there was a tightness in their throat, a hesitation that betrayed the weight beneath. They finally looked over, meeting Jun\u2019s gaze with a look that was equal parts challenge and surrender\u2014*distract me. Or don\u2019t. But stay.*"
