        "content": "Ser Kael\u2019s blade paused mid-swing, the practice steel hovering in the air as his sharp eyes locked onto the squire\u2019s trembling hands. The tremor was subtle\u2014barely there\u2014but to a man who had spent a lifetime reading the language of battle, it was as glaring as a war cry.\n\nFor a heartbeat, the training yard was silent. The wind still howled, the distant clatter of the castle still echoed, but Ser Kael did not move. His gaze flicked from the squire\u2019s hands to their face\u2014pale, set in a rigid mask of concentration, but with something flickering beneath the surface. Something *uncontrolled.*\n\nHis jaw tightened.\n\nHe had seen this before. Not in himself\u2014never in himself\u2014but in others. The way grief could seep into the bones, could make even the strongest arm falter. It was a weakness, yes. But it was not one born of laziness or cowardice. It was the kind of weakness that could be *forged* into strength, if handled correctly.\n\nSer Kael exhaled through his nose, slow and deliberate. Then, without a word, he turned and strode toward the weapons rack. The squire\u2019s breath hitched\u2014just slightly\u2014as if bracing for a rebuke. But Ser Kael did not speak. Instead, he selected a third practice blade from the rack, this one shorter, lighter, its edge dulled but its balance true. He tested its weight in his hand, then turned back to the squire.\n\n\"Today,\" he said, voice low and measured, \"we will not drill the high guard.\"\n\nThe squire blinked, their grip tightening reflexively around the hilt of their own blade. Ser Kael ignored the reaction. He stepped forward, closing the distance between them, and extended the shorter blade toward the squire, hilt-first.\n\n\"Take it.\"\n\nThe squire hesitated for only a heartbeat before reaching out and accepting the weapon. Ser Kael did not release it immediately. His fingers lingered on the hilt for a moment, his gaze locking onto the squire\u2019s.\n\n\"Today,\" he repeated, \"we will drill *precision.*\"\n\nHe stepped back, assuming a neutral stance, his own blade held loosely at his side. The squire mirrored him, confusion flickering across their face. Ser Kael did not explain. Instead, he raised his blade, the tip pointing toward the squire\u2019s chest.\n\n\"Strike me,\" he said.\n\nThe squire\u2019s eyes widened. \"Ser?\"\n\n\"Strike me,\" Ser Kael repeated, voice unyielding. \"Not with strength. With *precision.* Aim for my shoulder. Control your swing. If your blade wavers, you fail.\"\n\nThe squire swallowed hard, then adjusted their grip on the shorter blade. They took a breath, steadying themselves, before stepping forward and swinging. The strike was hesitant, the blade trembling slightly as it arced toward Ser Kael\u2019s shoulder. He did not move. The blade connected\u2014barely\u2014a dull *thud* of wood against steel.\n\nSer Kael did not flinch. He did not speak. He simply lowered his own blade and stepped back.\n\n\"Again.\"\n\nThe squire struck a second time. This time, the blade was steadier, the swing more controlled. Ser Kael\u2019s gaze flicked to their stance\u2014feet planted, weight balanced, elbow tucked. *Better.*\n\n\"Again.\"\n\nThe squire obeyed. And again. And again.\n\nSer Kael did not praise. He did not criticize. He simply stood, unyielding as stone, and let the squire strike. Each swing was a little surer, a little sharper, the tremble in their hands fading with each repetition. The yard was silent save for the *thud* of wood against steel, the squire\u2019s controlled breaths, the distant wind.\n\nAfter the tenth strike, Ser Kael raised a hand. The squire lowered their blade immediately, their chest heaving slightly. Ser Kael\u2019s gaze flicked over them\u2014shoulders squared, stance firm, hands steady. The tremor was gone.\n\n\"Good,\" he said.\n\nThe word was not praise. It was acknowledgment. A single, sharp syllable that cut through the silence like a blade.\n\n\"Now,\" he continued, voice low, \"we will drill the footwork. And you will *not* falter.\"\n\nHe turned away, striding toward the center of the yard. The squire followed, their steps lighter now, their grip sure. Ser Kael did not look back. He did not need to.\n\nThe lesson had been learned."
