        "content": "Ser Kael did not acknowledge the squire\u2019s unspoken realization. There was no need. A knight did not require validation for doing what was necessary.\n\nHe stopped at the center of the yard, where the frost had been trampled into slush by countless drills. The morning light slanted across the stones, casting long shadows that stretched like the fingers of some forgotten god. Ser Kael turned, his boots crunching over the uneven ground, and faced the squire with the same unyielding focus as before.\n\n\"Footwork is not about speed,\" he said, voice low and measured. \"It is about *control.* A knight who stumbles is a knight who dies. A knight who hesitates is a knight who fails.\"\n\nHe raised his blade, the practice steel catching the light as he assumed the starting stance\u2014feet shoulder-width apart, knees bent just enough to absorb a strike, weight balanced evenly. His free hand rested at his hip, fingers curled as if ready to draw a dagger.\n\n\"Observe.\"\n\nHe moved.\n\nNot with the fluid grace of a dancer, nor with the brute force of a brawler, but with the precise, economical motion of a man who had spent a lifetime perfecting the art of killing. His lead foot stepped forward, heel first, then rolled onto the ball as his trailing foot followed, shifting his weight seamlessly. The blade moved with him, a silver arc cutting through the air, controlled and deliberate.\n\n\"One step. Two. *Pivot.*\"\n\nHis body twisted, hips leading, shoulders following, the blade sweeping in a tight arc before resetting. The movement was effortless, yet every muscle in his body was engaged, every breath measured. He did not rush. He did not falter.\n\n\"Again.\"\n\nHe repeated the sequence, slower this time, his voice cutting through the silence like a blade.\n\n\"Your front foot must *lead.* Your weight must *shift.* If you lunge like a drunken peasant, you will leave your flank exposed. If you drag your feet like a plowman, you will be too slow to counter.\"\n\nHe stopped, blade lowered, and turned to the squire. His gaze was sharp, unrelenting.\n\n\"Now. *You.*\"\n\nThe squire hesitated for only a heartbeat before stepping forward, mirroring Ser Kael\u2019s stance. Their first movement was stiff, their weight shifting unevenly, the blade wavering slightly. Ser Kael\u2019s jaw tightened, but he did not speak. He simply watched, arms crossed, as the squire fumbled through the sequence.\n\n\"Again.\"\n\nThe squire tried once more. This time, their footwork was slightly better, their weight more balanced, but their blade still trembled. Ser Kael exhaled through his nose, slow and controlled.\n\n\"Your elbow is drifting. *Tuck it.* Your blade is too high. *Lower it.*\"\n\nThe squire adjusted immediately, their stance firming. Ser Kael gave no acknowledgment. None was needed.\n\n\"Again.\"\n\nThe squire obeyed. And again. And again.\n\nSer Kael did not praise. He did not criticize. He simply stood, unyielding as stone, and let the squire drill. The yard was silent save for the *scuff* of boots against frost, the squire\u2019s controlled breaths, the distant wind.\n\nAfter the tenth repetition, Ser Kael raised a hand. The squire lowered their blade immediately, their chest heaving slightly. Ser Kael\u2019s gaze flicked over them\u2014shoulders squared, stance firm, hands steady. The tremor was gone.\n\n\"Better,\" he said.\n\nThe word was not praise. It was acknowledgment. A single, sharp syllable that cut through the silence like a blade.\n\n\"Now,\" he continued, voice low, \"we will add the counter.\"\n\nHe stepped forward, blade raised, and assumed a defensive stance. The squire mirrored him, their eyes locked onto his, waiting.\n\n\"Strike,\" Ser Kael said.\n\nThe squire hesitated for only a heartbeat before lunging forward, their blade arcing toward his shoulder. Ser Kael did not move. The blade connected\u2014barely\u2014a dull *thud* of wood against steel.\n\n\"Again.\"\n\nThe squire struck a second time. This time, Ser Kael shifted his weight, pivoting on his lead foot, and brought his blade up in a sharp counter. The practice steel connected with the squire\u2019s blade with a sharp *crack*, knocking it aside.\n\n\"Your strike is too telegraphed,\" he said, voice unyielding. \"A knight does not warn his enemy. He *acts.*\"\n\nThe squire nodded, adjusting their grip on the blade. Ser Kael did not wait for them to recover. He lunged forward, his own blade a silver blur, and struck. The squire barely managed to block, their arms trembling with the force of the blow.\n\n\"Again.\"\n\nThe squire struck. Ser Kael countered. The squire blocked. Ser Kael pressed forward, his blade a relentless force, driving the squire back step by step. The yard echoed with the *crack* of wood against wood, the squire\u2019s ragged breaths, the crunch of frost beneath their boots.\n\nSer Kael did not relent. He did not slow. He simply *was*\u2014a force as unyielding as the stone beneath their feet.\n\n\"Faster,\" he said.\n\nThe squire obeyed.\n\nAnd for the first time that morning, Ser Kael allowed himself the faintest flicker of something that might have been approval.\n\nBut it was gone before it could take root.\n\nApproval was not his to give.\n\nIt was theirs to *earn.*"
